  "prompt": "Why is \"inglory\" not a word?",
  "response": "The word \"inglory\" is not commonly used in modern English, but it is technically a word. It combines the prefix \"in-\", meaning \"not\" or \"lacking,\" with \"glory,\" suggesting a lack of glory or something inglorious. However, it hasn't gained widespread usage, and \"inglorious\" is the more commonly accepted term to convey the absence of glory or honorable recognition. Language evolves over time, and certain forms become standardized while others fade away, which is why you might not frequently encounter \"inglory\" in contemporary contexts.",
